## Report Metadata

- Component: Envoy downstream HTTP/3, router, upstream HTTP/1 codec/pool
- Confirmed Envoy image:
  `envoyproxy/envoy-dev@sha256:d0d3873487c5184b4fc84b7b708019687a2fb58390f75358c685e7bba93e5a44`
- Source commit used for static source permalinks:
  `88a627accfac82e9f1fa0467ce1dadbe0f80b216`
- Reproduction Gist:
  <https://gist.github.com/ndkoo/0992d6220ebf96983369f228f50e3de6>

## Summary

Envoy can translate a downstream HTTP/3 request that is complete at the transport
layer (`HEADERS` with FIN / headers-only close) but still carries a nonzero
`Content-Length` into a complete upstream HTTP/1 request with unresolved body
debt.

In an HTTP/1 upstream deployment where the origin replies before reading the
declared body and keeps the connection reusable, the beginning of the next
Envoy-generated upstream request can be consumed as the first request's body.
The remaining bytes are then parsed by the origin as a new HTTP/1 request. This
was reproduced as a route-bypass/desync: direct `/pwn` was denied by Envoy, but
the second downstream H3 stream received the response for backend-parsed
`GET /pwn HTTP/1.1`.

## Affected Configuration

Confirmed vulnerable shape:

- downstream HTTP/3 enabled
- upstream HTTP/1 cluster
- upstream origin can send an early response before consuming the declared
  request body
- upstream HTTP/1 connection remains reusable after that response

## Impact

An attacker who can make HTTP/3 requests to Envoy can cause an HTTP/1 upstream
origin to process a request different from the one Envoy routed and authorized.
In the PoC:

- Envoy routes the second request as `/allowed`.
- The backend receives and responds to `GET /pwn HTTP/1.1`.
- Direct H3 access to `/pwn` returns `EDGE-DENY`.

This demonstrates HTTP request smuggling and route/policy bypass at the
HTTP/3-to-HTTP/1 translation boundary.

## Reproduction Artifacts

The Gist linked above contains:

- `STEP-BY-STEP-GUIDE.md`: environment-agnostic setup and execution steps
- `EXPECTED_OUTPUT.md`: expected output for the reproduction
- PoC code/config/scripts for downstream H3, HTTP/1 upstream, and Envoy config

The positive case is reproduced by:

```bash
bash /tmp/envoy-h3h1-bodydebt/run_remote.sh
```

## High-Signal Evidence

Direct `/pwn` is denied by Envoy:

```text
SINGLE stream=0 body='EDGE-DENY\n'
```

Exploit output for downstream H3 to upstream HTTP/1:

```text
FIRST stream=0 body='EARLY-OK'
SECOND stream=4 body='SMUGGLED-PWN method=GET path=/pwn req=2\n'
```

Backend log showing the body-debt boundary:

```text
REQ#1 GET /early cl=51
REQ#1 BODY_DEBT len=51 ascii=GET /allowed HTTP/1.1\r\nhost: localhost\r\nx-smuggle:
REQ#2 GET /pwn cl=0
```

The second H3 request sent by the client was `/allowed`, with
`x-smuggle: GET /pwn HTTP/1.1`. Envoy routed it as `/allowed`, but the HTTP/1
origin parsed the remaining bytes as a separate `/pwn` request.

## Root Cause

The issue is a mismatch between semantic request completion and body-byte
accounting at the HTTP/3-to-HTTP/1 translation boundary. Source permalinks below
are pinned to Envoy commit
`88a627accfac82e9f1fa0467ce1dadbe0f80b216`.

```text
Downstream H3 HEADERS+FIN
  Content-Length: N > 0, no DATA bytes
    -> EnvoyQuicServerStream::OnInitialHeadersComplete()
    -> headers-only close is forwarded as end_stream=true
    -> router/upstream codec preserves end_stream and Content-Length
    -> HTTP/1 RequestEncoderImpl emits Content-Length: N and finalizes request
    -> HTTP/1 origin sees a complete request with N bytes of body debt
    -> bytes from the next upstream request can satisfy that debt
    -> remaining bytes can be parsed by the origin as a new request
```

The key invariant that fails is:

```text
semantic request completion must not cross a protocol boundary until
Content-Length accounting has been reconciled with received DATA bytes
```

### 1. `Content-Length` Is Stored, but the Equality Check Is Deferred

[`source/common/quic/envoy_quic_stream.h#L147-L154`](https://github.com/envoyproxy/envoy/blob/88a627accfac82e9f1fa0467ce1dadbe0f80b216/source/common/quic/envoy_quic_stream.h#L147-L154)
records the declared length during header validation:

```cpp
if (header_name == "content-length") {
  size_t content_length = 0;
  Http::HeaderUtility::HeaderValidationResult result =
      Http::HeaderUtility::validateContentLength(
          header_value, override_stream_error_on_invalid_http_message,
          close_connection_upon_invalid_header_, content_length);
  content_length_ = content_length;
  return result;
}
```

The actual byte-count comparison is in
[`updateReceivedContentBytes()`](https://github.com/envoyproxy/envoy/blob/88a627accfac82e9f1fa0467ce1dadbe0f80b216/source/common/quic/envoy_quic_stream.h#L208-L220):

```cpp
void updateReceivedContentBytes(size_t payload_length, bool end_stream) {
  received_content_bytes_ += payload_length;
  if (!content_length_.has_value()) {
    return;
  }
  if (received_content_bytes_ > content_length_.value() ||
      (end_stream && received_content_bytes_ != content_length_.value() &&
       !(got_304_response_ && received_content_bytes_ == 0) && !(sent_head_request_))) {
    details_ = Http3ResponseCodeDetailValues::inconsistent_content_length;
    onStreamError(false);
  }
}
```

This is sound only if every path that marks the request complete calls the
accounting function with `end_stream=true`.

### 2. H3 Headers-Only Close Is Promoted to `end_stream=true`

[`EnvoyQuicServerStream::OnInitialHeadersComplete()`](https://github.com/envoyproxy/envoy/blob/88a627accfac82e9f1fa0467ce1dadbe0f80b216/source/common/quic/envoy_quic_server_stream.cc#L175-L183)
detects a headers-only close and sets `end_stream_decoded_` before body
accounting has run:

```cpp
const bool headers_only = fin_received() && highest_received_byte_offset() == NumBytesConsumed();
const bool end_stream =
    fin ||
    (headers_only && Runtime::runtimeFeatureEnabled("envoy.reloadable_features.quic_signal_"
                                                    "headers_only_to_http1_backend"));
if (end_stream) {
  end_stream_decoded_ = true;
}
```

The same function then forwards semantic completion to the HTTP filter chain:

[`source/common/quic/envoy_quic_server_stream.cc#L232-L235`](https://github.com/envoyproxy/envoy/blob/88a627accfac82e9f1fa0467ce1dadbe0f80b216/source/common/quic/envoy_quic_server_stream.cc#L232-L235)

```cpp
Http::RequestDecoder* decoder = request_decoder_->get().ptr();
if (decoder != nullptr) {
  decoder->decodeHeaders(std::move(headers), /*end_stream=*/end_stream);
}
```

The later body-availability path skips decoding and accounting when
`end_stream_decoded_` is already set:

[`source/common/quic/envoy_quic_server_stream.cc#L276-L286`](https://github.com/envoyproxy/envoy/blob/88a627accfac82e9f1fa0467ce1dadbe0f80b216/source/common/quic/envoy_quic_server_stream.cc#L276-L286)

```cpp
// If this call is triggered by an empty frame with FIN which is not from peer
// but synthesized by stream itself upon receiving HEADERS with FIN or
// TRAILERS, do not deliver end of stream here. Because either decodeHeaders
// already delivered it or decodeTrailers will be called.
bool skip_decoding = (buffer->length() == 0 && !fin_read_and_no_trailers) || end_stream_decoded_;
if (!skip_decoding) {
  if (fin_read_and_no_trailers) {
    end_stream_decoded_ = true;
  }
  updateReceivedContentBytes(buffer->length(), fin_read_and_no_trailers);
```

For the PoC shape, the H3 stream is treated as complete from headers, but
`received_content_bytes_ == 0` is never reconciled against the nonzero
`content_length_` before the request crosses into upstream forwarding.

### 3. Router and Upstream Codec Preserve the Premature End-Stream Bit

The upstream request initialization forwards the same `end_stream` value into
the upstream filter manager:

[`source/common/router/upstream_request.cc#L454-L456`](https://github.com/envoyproxy/envoy/blob/88a627accfac82e9f1fa0467ce1dadbe0f80b216/source/common/router/upstream_request.cc#L454-L456)

```cpp
filter_manager_->requestHeadersInitialized();
filter_manager_->streamInfo().setRequestHeaders(*parent_.downstreamHeaders());
filter_manager_->decodeHeaders(*parent_.downstreamHeaders(), end_stream);
```

The last upstream filter sends it to the selected upstream codec unchanged:

[`source/common/router/upstream_codec_filter.cc#L51-L65`](https://github.com/envoyproxy/envoy/blob/88a627accfac82e9f1fa0467ce1dadbe0f80b216/source/common/router/upstream_codec_filter.cc#L51-L65)

```cpp
// This is the last stop in the filter chain: take the headers and ship them to the codec.
Http::FilterHeadersStatus UpstreamCodecFilter::decodeHeaders(Http::RequestHeaderMap& headers,
                                                             bool end_stream) {
  ASSERT(callbacks_->upstreamCallbacks());
  if (!callbacks_->upstreamCallbacks()->upstream()) {
    latched_headers_ = headers;
    latched_end_stream_ = end_stream;
    return Http::FilterHeadersStatus::StopAllIterationAndWatermark;
  }

  ENVOY_STREAM_LOG(trace, "proxying headers", *callbacks_);
  calling_encode_headers_ = true;
  const Http::Status status =
      callbacks_->upstreamCallbacks()->upstream()->encodeHeaders(headers, end_stream);
```

For HTTP upstreams, that call is a direct wrapper over the protocol encoder:

[`source/extensions/upstreams/http/http/upstream_request.h#L70-L72`](https://github.com/envoyproxy/envoy/blob/88a627accfac82e9f1fa0467ce1dadbe0f80b216/source/extensions/upstreams/http/http/upstream_request.h#L70-L72)

```cpp
Envoy::Http::Status encodeHeaders(const Envoy::Http::RequestHeaderMap& headers,
                                  bool end_stream) override {
  return request_encoder_->encodeHeaders(headers, end_stream);
}
```

No step in this forwarding path converts the inconsistent H3 message into an
error, strips the stale `Content-Length`, or forces a body write.

### 4. HTTP/1 Encoding Emits the Stale `Content-Length` and Finalizes

The HTTP/1 encoder emits the request headers, sees that `Content-Length` is
already present, and therefore does not replace it with `Content-Length: 0`:

[`source/common/http/http1/codec_impl.cc#L155-L177`](https://github.com/envoyproxy/envoy/blob/88a627accfac82e9f1fa0467ce1dadbe0f80b216/source/common/http/http1/codec_impl.cc#L155-L177)

```cpp
headers.iterate(
    [this, &header_values, formatter](const HeaderEntry& header) -> HeaderMap::Iterate {
      absl::string_view key_to_use = header.key().getStringView();
      uint32_t key_size_to_use = header.key().size();
      // Translate :authority -> host so that upper layers do not need to deal with this.
      if (key_size_to_use > 1 && key_to_use[0] == ':' && key_to_use[1] == 'a') {
        key_to_use = absl::string_view(header_values.HostLegacy.get());
        key_size_to_use = header_values.HostLegacy.get().size();
      }

      // Skip all headers starting with ':' that make it here.
      if (key_to_use[0] == ':') {
        return HeaderMap::Iterate::Continue;
      }

      encodeFormattedHeader(key_to_use, header.value().getStringView(), formatter);
      return HeaderMap::Iterate::Continue;
    });

if (headers.ContentLength()) {
  saw_content_length = true;
}
```

The header-only fallback only writes `Content-Length: 0` when a content length
was not already seen:

[`source/common/http/http1/codec_impl.cc#L192-L215`](https://github.com/envoyproxy/envoy/blob/88a627accfac82e9f1fa0467ce1dadbe0f80b216/source/common/http/http1/codec_impl.cc#L192-L215)

```cpp
if (saw_content_length || disable_chunk_encoding_) {
  chunk_encoding_ = false;
} else {
  if (status && (*status < 200 || *status == 204)) {
    // For 1xx and 204 responses, do not send the chunked encoding header or enable chunked
    // encoding: https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7230#section-3.3.1
    chunk_encoding_ = false;
  } else if (status && *status == 304) {
    // For 304 response, since it should never have a body, we should not need to chunk_encode at
    // all.
    chunk_encoding_ = false;
  } else if (end_stream && !is_response_to_head_request_) {
    // If this is a headers-only stream, append an explicit "Content-Length: 0" unless it's a
    // response to a HEAD request.
    // For 204s and 1xx where content length is disallowed, don't append the content length but
    // also don't chunk encode.
    // Also do not add content length for requests which should not have a
    // body, per https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7230#section-3.3.2
    if (!bodiless_request) {
      encodeFormattedHeader(header_values.ContentLength.get(), "0", formatter);
    }
    chunk_encoding_ = false;
```

Finally, the preserved `end_stream=true` completes request encoding:

[`source/common/http/http1/codec_impl.cc#L239-L240`](https://github.com/envoyproxy/envoy/blob/88a627accfac82e9f1fa0467ce1dadbe0f80b216/source/common/http/http1/codec_impl.cc#L239-L240)

```cpp
if (end_stream) {
  endEncode();
```

The result is an upstream HTTP/1 request that Envoy considers fully encoded and
eligible for the normal response/reuse flow, while the origin still interprets
the preserved `Content-Length: N` as body bytes owed on the connection. If the
origin responds early and keeps the connection open, bytes from Envoy's next
upstream request can be consumed as the prior request body, leaving attacker
controlled bytes to be parsed as a separate backend request.


## Suggested Fix Direction

Before propagating `end_stream=true` from initial H3 headers, Envoy should
reconcile the header-only close with any declared request body. A downstream H3
request with `Content-Length: N > 0` and no DATA bytes should be rejected as an
inconsistent message, or Envoy should otherwise prevent it from being forwarded
as a complete upstream request carrying a nonzero `Content-Length`.

The important invariant is:

```text
semantic request completion must not cross a protocol boundary until
Content-Length accounting has been reconciled with received DATA bytes
```

## Report Scope

This report intentionally claims:

- confirmed HTTP/3-to-HTTP/1 request smuggling
- confirmed route/policy bypass in the included controlled configuration

It does not claim:

- bypass of Envoy-native auth filters in every deployment
- cross-user response poisoning
- request smuggling on non-HTTP/1 upstream protocols
